<section xml:id="sec-quaternions">
	<title>Quaternion algebra</title>
	<introduction>
		In this section, we assume that <m>F</m> is a field with the property that <m>2\neq 0</m>. We define a Quaternion algebra over <m>F</m>.
	</introduction>
	<definition xml:id="def-quaternions">
		<title>(Quaternion)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>a,b\in F</m> be nonzero elements. Consider a <m>4</m>-dimensional vector space <m>Q</m> over <m>F</m> with basis <m>\{1,i,j,k\}</m>. We write <m>\alpha\cdot1=\alpha</m> for any <m>\alpha\in F</m>. Thus <m>Q=\{x_0+x_1i+x_2j+x_3k:x_i\in F\}</m>. We make <m>Q</m> a ring by defining 
			<men>i^2=a,\;j^2=b,\;\text{and}\; ij=-ji=k</men>
			and
			<men xml:id="multiplication-by-scalars-quaternions">\alpha i=i\alpha,\;\alpha j=j\alpha,\;\text{and}\;\alpha k=k\alpha\quad\text{for all}\;\alpha\in F.</men>
			Hence <me>ik=i(ij)=(i^2)j=aj\quad\text{and}\quad jk=j(ij)=j(-ji)=-(j^2)i=-bi</me> and <me>ki=(ij)i=-(ji)i=-aj\quad\text{and}\quad kj=(ij)j=i(j^2)=bi.</me>
			Given <m>x_0+x_1i+x_2j+x_3k\in Q</m> and <m>y_0+y_1i+y_2j+y_3k\in Q</m> their multiplication is defined as follows.
			<md><mrow>(x_0+x_1i+x_2j+x_3k)(y_0+y_1i+y_2j+y_3k)\amp=(x_0y_0)+(x_0y_1)i+(x_0y_2)j+(x_0y_3)k</mrow><mrow>\amp\;\quad+ (x_1y_0)i+(x_1y_1) a+(x_1y_2)k+(x_1y_3)a j</mrow><mrow>\amp\;\quad\quad +(x_2y_0)j-(x_2y_1)k+(x_2y_2)b-(x_2y_3)bi</mrow><mrow>\amp\;\quad\quad\quad +(x_3y_0)k-(x_3y_1)aj+(x_3y_2)bi-(x_3y_3)ab.</mrow><mrow>\amp=(x_0y_0+x_1y_1a+x_2y_2b-x_3y_3ab)</mrow><mrow>\amp\;\quad+(x_0y_1+x_1y_0-x_2y_3b+x_3y_2b)i</mrow><mrow>\amp\;\quad\quad+(x_0y_2+x_1y_3a+x_2y_0-x_3y_1a)j</mrow><mrow>\amp\;\quad\quad\quad+(x_0y_3+x_1y_2-x_2y_1+x_3y_0)k</mrow></md>
			<p>
				This also shows that <m>1</m> is the unity of <m>Q</m>, and <m>Q</m> is an <m>F</m>-algebra.
			</p>
			<p>
				The algebra <m>Q</m> is called a <term>quaternion algebra over <m>F</m></term> and it is denoted by <m>(a,b)_F</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<convention>
		<statement>
			We say that a quaternion algebra <m>Q=(a,b)_F</m> is <term>generated by <m>i</m> and <m>j</m> over <m>F</m> with relations</term>.
				<men xml:id="defining-relations-quaternions">i^2=a,\;j^2=b,\;\text{and}\; ij=-ji=k</men>
		</statement>
	</convention>
	<example xml:id="Hamiltonian-algebra">
		<title>(Hamiltonian Quaternion Algebra)</title>
		<statement>
			The Hamiltonian quaternion algebra is the quaternion algebra over <m>\R</m> generated by <m>i</m> and <m>j</m> such that
			<men xml:id="defining-relations-Hamiltonian">i^2=-1,\;j^2=-1,\;\text{and}\;ij=-ji=k.</men>
			The Hamiltonian quaternion is denoted by <m>\mathbb{H}=(-1,-1)_{\R}</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="split-quaternion">
		<title>(<m>2\times 2</m> matrices as quaternions)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>F</m> be a field and <m>b\in F</m> a nonzero element. Consider the following matrices.
			<me>\mathcal{I}=\begin{pmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp -1\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathcal{J}=\begin{pmatrix}0\amp b\\1\amp 0\end{pmatrix}</me>
			The quaternion algebra generated by <m>\mathcal{I}</m> and <m>\mathcal{J}</m> is all <m>2\times 2</m> matrices over <m>F</m>, <m>M_2(F)</m>. This follows because
			<me>I_2=\begin{pmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{pmatrix},\quad \mathcal{I}=\begin{pmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp -1\end{pmatrix},\quad\mathcal{J}=\begin{pmatrix}0\amp b\\1\amp 0\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathcal{IJ}=\begin{pmatrix}0\amp b\\-1\amp 0\end{pmatrix}</me>
			is an <m>F</m>-vector space basis of <m>M_2(F)</m>.
			Furthermore,
			<me>\mathcal{I}^2=I_2,\quad\mathcal{J}^2=b I_2,\quad\text{and}\quad\mathcal{IJ}=-\mathcal{JI}.</me>
			Therefore, <m>M_2(F)</m> is a quaternion algebra.
		</statement>
	</example>
</section>